2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a Latinist, a clerk who wrote documents in Latin, from Anglo-Norman French <i>latinier</i>, <i>latim(m)ier</i>. Latin was more or less the universal language of official documents in the Middle Ages, displaced only gradually by the vernacular – in England, by Anglo-Norman French at first, and eventually by English."],"variants":[{"name":"Latner","meanings":["English: occupational name for a worker in or maker of latten or brass, from Middle English <i>latoun</i> ‘brass’ (Old French <i>laton</i>). This name may sometimes have been confused with   Latimer  .","Altered form of German   Lattner   or   Lettner  ."]},{"name":"Lattimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Latimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattimer","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattner","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  .","German: occupational name for a carpenter who prepared or used laths or slats, from Middle High German <i>latte</i> ‘slat, lath’ + <i>-n</i> (plural suffix) + the agent suffix <i>-er</i>."]}]},{"name":"Katherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of   Katherine  , also occasionally used in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":1,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Katherine le Latimer was born in 1336, in Northamptonshire, England, her father, Sir Thomas le Latimer, was 66 and her mother, Lora de Hastings, was 6